name: Callejeros
comments: Neighborhood rock band, Argentina formed in Villa Celina, Province of Buenos Aires. Its first name was Río Verde. At its most popular moment, a flare during a recital by the band at the Disco República de Cromañón, on December 30, 2004, set fire to cloths located on the ceiling and produced a tragedy. The balance was 194 dead and more than 700 injured. Most of the deaths occurred from severe respiratory problems caused by inhaling carbon monoxide. The incident began around 10:30 p.m. that day, when Callejeros was performing the third theme of the show. It is known that there were at least 2,000 people and there are several indications that the bowling alley was occupied beyond capacity. On August 19, 2009, a sentence was passed in the criminal case, the musicians who were members of Callejeros were acquitted. In April 2011, the Chamber of Cassation reviewed the sentence handed down two years earlier, this time condemning all the members of the band as necessary participants in the crime of "Arson followed by death in a royal contest with active bribery." On October 17, 2012, the Criminal Cassation Chamber sentenced the entire band, with immediate compliance with the sentence to all those convicted (fourteen years in total). On August 6, 2014, the Supreme Court granted the appeal extraordinary presented by the band, setting them free pending a new ruling. However, in April 2016 the Criminal Cassation Chamber, upon reviewing the ruling, sentenced Patricio Santos Fontanet to 7 years in prison and 5 years to the rest of the musicians.

comments: Faroese poet best known for his satirical poems, love poems, tales and songs. He worked as a school teacher for some years, but most of his life he worked as a sheep farmer and a laborer.

name: Bill Ashford
comments: Radio programmer turning songwriter, lyricist, arranger and producer - and turning back to radio work.

name: Ayah Marar
comments: Singer-songwriter DJ, radio show host and label owner based in the UK

name: Broke
comments: Masked DJ who keeps their identity hidden

name: Stewart MacPherson
comments: Radio announcer, tour promoter, singer and record label owner.

name: Árni Johnsen
comments: Troubadour and singer-songwriter born in Vestmannaeyjar

name: Ana Kiro
comments: Actress and singer born in Arzúa, Galicia

name: Los Lord's
comments: Group from the Balearic Islands consisting of Margarita Llambrias Guzmán [Ita Llambias] (vocals), Benito Permuy Fernández (lead guitar), Mateo Sintes (guitar), Guillermo Cardona Mercadal (bass), Antonio Server Pons (drums) and Josep María Cardus Pubill (keyboards)

name: Bisser Kirov
comments: Singer, who in the press was called the most popular Bulgarian in the USSR. Kirov called Russia his creative homeland.

name: YU-all Stars 1977
comments: One-off band consisting of jazz musicians from various parts of ex-Yugoslavia

name: Francisco Céspedes
comments: Cuban-born, Grammy-nominated, Latin American singer, musician and songwriter born in Santa Clara, Cuba. He is currently a naturalized Mexican and best known for his 1998 song, "Vida loca".

name: Lyda Zamora
comments: Singer and actress born in Bucaramanga, Santander

name: Los Pekes
comments: Band from Madrid consisting of José Pedro López Savorit "Pepe" (guitar), Jesús Provencio (rhythm guitar), Pedro Provencio (drums), Benito Gil (bass, arranger), María Esther Alvárez (vocals, 1963-?), José Francisco Cervera "Francis" (bass, 1964-?) and Fernando Muñoz (organ, 1967-?).

name: Butch Cornell
comments: Jazz music organist, pianist and composer.

name: Los Churumbeles de España
comments: Folklore band from Madrid. Founded by José Fernández Ruiz ("Pepe Fernández") (1914-2003) and others. This first formation was called "Sexteto Mizar" or "Los Maestros Cantores". By 1949, after expanding the formation with other musicians, the group went to America, where it spent its entire recording career, already under the name of "Los Churumbeles de España".

name: Édouard-Léon Scott de Martinville
comments: Writer, publisher and inventor, who invented the earliest known sound recording device, the phonautograph, which was patented in France on 25 March 1857.

name: Selina Lannie
comments: Vocalist and later member of the Danish all-female band Nelson Can

name: Philippine & Théo
comments: Duo consisting of Théo Isambourg and Philippine Zadéo

name: Johnny Laboriel
comments: Singer from Mexico City and one of the pioneers of Mexican Rock 'n Roll. He became a member of Los Rebeldes Del Rock in 1960. By 1964 he left to pursue a solo career.

name: Arnulfo M. Vega
comments: Singer, songwriter and lyricist and member of the Mexican group Los Impala

name: Los Impala [MX]
comments: Vocal group consisting of Laura Olivia Solis, Humberto Basurto and Arnulfo M. Vega

name: Royal Quartet
comments: String quartet established in 1998 at The Fryderyk Chopin University of Music, Warsaw

name: Fat Ammon
comments: Beach music singer and drummer. He co-founded The Rhondels with Bill Deal .

name: Ben J. Bradley
comments: Song writer and piano dealer from Kentucky.

name: Trova
comments: Trio  formed by Ruth MacKenzie (vocals), Jeffrey Willkomm (vocals, electric bas)] and Eric Peltoniemi (vocals, guitar, songwriter).

name: The Dirty Mac
comments: Supergroup put together by Lennon for the TV special entitled "The Rolling Stones Rock and Roll Circus."

name: Mudcrutch
comments: Southern rock band from Gainesville, Florida, best known for being the band that introduced Tom Petty to fame. They were initially active in the early 1970s, then broke up after Tom Petty and several members formed The Heartbreakers. Mudcrutch reformed in 2007 with most of the original lineup.

name: Dave Kusworth
comments: Rock musician and songwriter from Birmingham

name: The Waltones
comments: Power pop band based in Manchester, England.

name: Thomas Stanley Brown
comments: Brown was studying poetry in Cambridge, Massachusetts and was a huge fan of Parsons. His music inspired Brown to write a poem and send it to Parsons to consider setting it to music.

name: Eileen Farrell
comments: Soprano vocalist.  Farrell started as an opera singer, but by 1960, she was also singing standards.  Farrell was a professor of music at Indiana University's School of Music from 1971 to 1980.

name: Tullio Carminati
comments: Actor and singer, best known in the USA as the archetypical "latin lover".

name: Chase Webster
comments: Country and rockabilly singer and songwriter. Re-emerged in Australia

name: Maxïmo Park
comments: English indie rock band founded in Newcastle

name: The Subways
comments: Rock band from Welwyn Garden City

name: Hal
comments: Indie rock band based in Dublin

name: A.C. Williams

name: Maxwell Davis
comments: R&B tenor saxophonist, songwriter, arranger and record producer

name: Sam Ling
comments: One of the four brothers who founded the blues/R&B label Modern Records .  He used the name Sam Ling as a songwriting pseudonym - although he was not a songwriter - to obtain undeserved royalties from the works written by African American musicians who recorded for the Biharis.

name: Eddie Kirkland
aliases: Eddie Kirkland and His House Rockers
comments: Born in Jamaica to a 12-year old mother, Kirkland was raised in Alabama. He was a blues guitarist, harmonica player, singer and songwriter.  Kirkland played with John Lee Hooker between 1949 and 1962.

name: Embrace [GB]
comments: Post-Britpop band from Bailiff Bridge, Brighouse, West Yorkshire

name: Nat Stuckey
comments: Country music performer and songwriter from Texas

name: Corou de Berra
comments: Group of traditional music from Berre les Alpes.

name: Bob Haggart
comments: Dixieland jazz and swing double bassist and composer.  Haggart was an original member and co-founder of the Bob Crosby Band led by Bob Crosby .  He stayed with the band until 1942, leaving to do session work.  Haggart played in many other groups in the 1950s and 1960s, including stints with several of Bob Crosby's bands of the 1960s.

name: Dan Fisher
comments: Songwriter, theatrical producer, author and publisher.

name: Pony Poindexter
comments: Jazz saxophonist.  Poindexter was one of the earliest of the bop-oriented saxophonists to regularly play soprano.  He also occasionally sang.

name: William Miller
comments: One of the founders of the Hull Records record label in New York city. Miller was also a musician (piano), songwriter, A&R executive and producer. He was the father of The Miller Sisters who recorded for the Herald and Hull labels.

name: James Sheppard
comments: R&B singer and songwriter from New York.

name: Eddie Boyd
aliases: Eddie Boyd and His Chess Men
Little Eddie Boyd and His Boogie Band
comments: Blues piano player, singer and songwriter

name: Andy Gibson [US1]
comments: Arranger, composer, trumpet player, and songwriter from Ohio. He was a musical director for King Records from 1955 until 1960.

name: Roy Alfred
comments: Mainly a lyricist, Alfred occasionally wrote music

name: The Chuck Wagon Gang
comments: Southern Gospel group founded in 1936 in Texas.

name: Hardwell
comments: Electro house DJ, record producer and remixer from Breda, North Brabant

name: DRS Big Band
comments: The DRS radio station's big band, which also included non-Swiss artists. It also uses other names like Unterhaltungorchester des DRS, DRS-Big Band Zürich etc.

name: Guy Bonnet
comments: Author, composer and singer born in Avignon, France. He wrote the lyrics for the French entry in the Eurovision Song Contest 1968.

name: Joe Poston
comments: Jazz saxophonist and composer born in Alexandria, Louisiana
